<p class="body">Nicaragua produces specialty coffee that competes with Panama Geisha lots at a meaningfully lower price point. The 2026 Geisha harvest from <a href="https://elquetzal.coffee/collections/geisha" rel="nofollow noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" style="color: var(--gold); text-decoration: none; border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(201,168,76,0.35);">Finca El Quetzal in Matagalpa</a> cupped at 87 points in its second year of production, with the same jasmine, peach, and tea-like clarity that defines the Geisha category, on volcanic soil at 1,200+ MASL that the wider specialty market still under-appreciates. The country's other competition-grade lots come from family farms in Jinotega and Nueva Segovia that have spent the post-civil-war decades moving from commodity supply into competition-grade specialty. The cup is real. The pricing is still in transition. This guide explains why.</p>

<p class="body">Three things distinguish Nicaraguan specialty from its Central American neighbors: cool-night microclimates that compensate for elevations sometimes below the textbook specialty threshold, generational family ownership that produces real lot-level traceability without large-estate marketing, and a varietal mix that mirrors what is happening in the highest-end Panama and Colombia lots (Geisha, Java, Pacamara, Maracaturra) at price points that have not yet caught up with the cup quality. If you are buying for a roasting program, a serious home setup, or a green coffee inventory, Nicaragua is one of the most undervalued specialty origins in the world right now.</p>

